  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Mary Carpenter is sending drawings by her sister and herself, accompanied by works of other artists, for the anti-slavery fair. Some of Mary Carpenter&apos;s pupils are also sending offerings. She tells of the residences and professions of her three brothers. Having read the National Anti-Slavery Standard with great interest, Mary Carpenter regrets &quot;that there are so many divisions among the Abolitionists.&quot; She remarks that William Lloyd Garrison &quot;seems to me to mistake what was the position of the Dissenters before the repeal of the Test &amp; Corporation Act.&quot; She explains the true facts. She refers to the persecution of abolitionists in America and the good fortune of colored people in England.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Much of this letter is crossed out, but it is still legible.</subfield>
  </datafield>
